Raspberry Palmiers 💖 Just 3 ingredients, so easy to make and the perfect heart-shaped cookie for Valentine’s Day!  Full recipe is on our website (link in bio) or BOOKMARK the recipe below 👇  RASPBERRY PALMIERS (makes 2 dozen) 14 oz puff pastry, thawed  1/2 oz freeze dried raspberries (linked on our amazon page) 1/2 cup granulated sugar, divided Optional: 2 oz white chocolate + more freeze dried raspberries for garnish Add the raspberries to a food processor and pulse into a fine powder.  Add ⅔ of the sugar to a bowl, then sift the raspberry powder into the sugar and discard the seeds. Whisk until well combined. Place puff pastry on a clean surface, then sprinkle with remaining ⅓ cup of (plain) sugar. Lightly roll out the rectangle with a rolling pin. Flip over the puff pastry, then sprinkle liberally with raspberry sugar. (NOTE: you may have sugar leftover. Just use enough to fully coat the puff pastry in an even layer.) Press it in with your hands, then use a rolling pin to roll it out. Most store bought puff pastry will be about 10x11 inches, but ours was a bit bigger, so we rolled it to about 13x14 inches. Fold the longer section of your puff pastry in half to mark the middle point. Then fold each end a little less than halfway to the middle and sprinkle with more raspberry sugar. Make another fold, folding each end towards the middle. Sprinkle on a little more regular sugar. Fold again so the two sides meet and press down gently with a rolling pin. Place in the freezer for 30 minutes. Preheat oven to 400˚F. Remove from freezer and cut into ½-inch thick slices. Space about 2 inches apart on parchment paper and bake for 8-10 minutes, then flip with a spatula and cook for another 4-5 minutes, until golden brown and crispy. Let cool, then dip in melted white chocolate and sprinkle with crushed freeze dried raspberries. #valentinesday #palmier #raspberry #whitechocolate

PAY TRANSPARENCY IS IN💸 This one is for all the latinas and the immigrants out there who see videos from influencers just like this one but rarely see themselves in this type of content.💕 THIS IS POSSIBLE FOR YOU. Even if you grew up poor, even if you can barely imagine these numbers, even if you’re an immigrant who has struggled their whole life, even if you feel like every single force in this country is working against you. I’m here to tell you that this is possible for us. I started posting content on TikTok in February 2022 when I was at my lowest career wise. I was so incredibly lost and had no idea what to do next after closing down my wedding photography business of 6 years.  I had always dreamed of being my own boss, of making money through my own creativity on my own terms. After closing down my business and working random freelance jobs for a while, I knew that I needed to figure something out ASAP or start applying for office jobs. At the time, I was hunting down social media jobs/anything that would let me use my photography skills so I would still get to be ✨creative✨ as a job.  I swear it felt like fate when my FYP started serving me a ton of these “what I made as an influencer last year/last month/what I charge for brand deals” type videos. I would watch them over and over and would hear that little whisper in my head that said“I think I could do that too…”  At the time, my brother and I had just moved into our new apartment, and I was spending all my time on Facebook Marketplace hunting down furniture as I had absolutely no money but very high standards and expensive taste.😭 Thrifting was the only other love I’ve ever known and focusing on my apartment gave me so much joy in a time where my mental health was hardcore struggling.  My brother saw how soul crushing the job search was for me and encouraged me to start posting on TikTok and take it seriously for one or two months to see what would happen. Two years later and HERE WE ARE!🤗 I have never made this much money in my entire life and NEVER thought I would be seeing these numbers at this point in my life (but keep in mind these numbers are PRE TAX). My one goal in life has always been to take care of my parents so that they could finally rest. So that they could leave jobs paying the smallest wage imaginable, doing manual labor as they grow older, and experiencing both casual and overt racism in the workplace. I’m so excited to be one step closer to that goal. I need you to start asking yourself: why not you? Why not? Like seriously why not? My whole life changed when I started asking myself that question. It’s not too late to start posting. It’s not too late to become a content creator if that’s what you’ve been wanting to do for months/years. It’s not too late! There’s room for all of us. One day, after one of my kids opened a @Babybel cheese, they asked if we could save the wax. It was one of those things where I was like, “Yeah, sure, okay” because I was doing thirty other things at the same time. But then we kept adding to it. It became this weird and cute thing we did together—eat a Babybel cheese, then add the wax to the tower in the cabinet and mark a tally on our sheet. We decided we’d make a candle one day. Well, that one day was today! We melted the wax, found a jar, added a birthday candle in the middle, and voila! My kids were PUMPED, and it was a really fun experiment to do together, tbh. #backflow #infectioncontrol closing on the suction at the dentist. Backflow protectors should be mandatory everywhere.  🦠🤮BACKFLOW🤮🦠 Closing on the saliva ejector creates negative pressure and can lead to backflow. There are backflow protectors available but not all offices use them, dental professionals are trained on maintaining the lines, running the lines in between patients and at the end of the day.  The CDC states, “Although no adverse health effects associated with the saliva ejector have been reported, dental health care personnel (DHCP) should be aware that backflow could occur when they use a saliva ejector. DHCP should not advise patients to close their lips tightly around the tip of the saliva ejector to evacuate oral fluids. DHCP should contact the manufacturer of the dental unit to review proper use and maintenance procedures, including appropriate cleaning and disinfection methods.” Dental offices should be running their dental water lines in the am, in between pts, and at the end of the day, we should also be shocking our systems, in addition to testing our dental unit waterlines, and changing our traps. Read: Passing the dental unit waterline test: 4 steps you need to know by Amanda Hill, BSDH, RDH Watch: VIDCAST: Is This the Most Overlooked Area in Infection Control? Sharing the easiest and most comforting soup with tips on how to perfect EGG DROP SOUP from Papa tea himself! 🥹 Recipe: Egg drop soup  Serves 1-2 1/3 cup frozen peas, carrots corn, mixed together  2 cups chicken broth, low sodium 2 large eggs, whisked  1/2 tsp kosher salt (adjust with less if using table salt) 1/2 tsp chicken bouillon  1/2 tsp sugar  1/8 tsp ground white pepper  1/8 tsp turmeric powder (for color) Sesame oil to taste  Green onions for garnish  Slurry: 2 tbsp cornstarch  3 tbsp water  1. In a small pot, add chicken broth, salt, chicken bouillon, sugar, white pepper, turmeric powder and bring to a boil.  2. Combine cornstarch and water well to ensure that there aren’t any clumps. 3. Once broth is boiling, pour in slurry while stirring broth. It will thicken up instantly.  4. Add frozen veggies and a splash of sesame oil. Boil for 2-3 minutes. 5. Reduce heat to medium-low (make sure broth is no longer boiling). Do not stir. Pour in half of the eggs in a very slow and small stream. Carefully stir 1-2 times then pour in the other half and stir 1-2 times to create egg ribbons. Leave it alone. 6. Turn the heat to high. Bring to a boil and immediately turn off the heat.  7. Garnish with sliced green onions and enjoy!  #eggdropsoup #eggflowersoup #chinesefood #takeoutfood #easyrecipe #asianrecipe

Egg drop soup’s sexy cousin  1 1/2 cups frozen sweet corn 1 cup thinly sliced chicken breast (I used two thin sliced breasts) 1 tsp cornstarch  1 tsp oyster sauce  32oz carton of chicken or bone broth (4 cups) 1 Tbsp soy sauce 1/2 tsp garlic powder 1/2 tsp turmeric  1/2 tsp chicken bouillon powder 1 tsp white pepper Cornstarch slurry (3 Tbsp cornstarch + 4 Tbsp water)  3 eggs mixed w/ 1 Tbsp water 1 tsp sesame oil Give your corn a rough chop and thinly slice your chicken breast. Season chicken with cornstarch and oyster sauce. Bring your chicken/bone broth to a boil and add in your soy sauce and seasonings. Pour in your cornstarch slurry as you stir and wait for the broth to thicken just a bit. Once thickened, add in chicken and cook for a minute. Add in corn and prepare your egg mixture. Turn the heat down and make sure your broth is not bubbling to avoid your soup from getting cloudy. Slowly pour in your egg mixture as you stir to create long egg ribbons. Cut the heat and add in sesame oil. Garnish with lots of green onion razzle dazzle and enjoy!

Weyes Blood’s most popular album Titanic Rising is an ethereal listen that feels like a warm blanket in times of pain. Weyes Blood’s vocals portray a motherly aura that beautifully pairs with her instrumentals, whether it’s folksy guitars or synths. She takes many influences from 70s soft rock, with inspiration from artists such as Joni Mitchell and the Carpenters. The lyrical content is very much all over the place. In the opening track, Weyes Blood looks back on the simpler times of childhood. She also discusses the difficulty of dating in today’s society, and climate change is a central theme with Titanic being used as a metaphor. This album is a standard for today’s soft rock, folk, and indie rock. Coming at the end of the 2010s, this is one of the best of the decade. #recommendations #review #aotd #music #fyp #album #weyesblood #softrock #indierock #folkrock

crockpot tomato basil chicken pasta 🍝✨🤭 recipe deets below!  what you’ll need:  2 lbs Chicken breasts  1 (28 oz) can fire roasted crushed tomatoes 1 cup chicken broth 1 cup heavy cream 1/2 cup grated parmesan cheese 1/4 cup sun-dried tomatoes, chopped 1/4 cup fresh basil, chopped 1 tbsp minced garlic  1 tbsp italian seasoning  1 1/2 tsp salt  1/2 tsp pepper Cooked pasta of your choice (I used brown rice pasta)  Topped with freshly chopped basil and grated parmesan cheese  Instructions:  1. Place the chicken breasts in the bottom of the crockpot.   2. In a mixing bowl, combine crushed tomatoes, chicken broth, heavy cream, parmesan cheese, sun-dried tomatoes, fresh basil, minced garlic, italian seasoning, salt, and pepper. Mix well.  3. Pour the tomato-cream mixture over the chicken in the crockpot and make sure it’s well coated.   4. Cook on high for about 2 1/2 hours or until the chicken is fully cooked.   5. 30 minutes before it’s done, use two forks to shred the chicken in the crockpot.   6. Cook your favorite pasta according to the package instructions then pour into the crockpot and give everything a good mix.   7. Taste and add more salt & pepper as needed. Serve immediately with some freshly chopped basil and parmesan cheese. Enjoy!    #easyweeknightmeals #easyhealthydinner #easyhealthydinneridea #makedinnerwithme #healthydinnerideas

This has been in our meal rotation for the last 4 years & it never gets old ✨🤩 recipe deets below!!  Zuppa Toscana 🤤 what you’ll need:  1 lb ground Italian chicken 1 lb ground Italian pork (can double the chicken if you don’t like pork) 1 small yellow onion, diced 6 cups chicken stock 2 lbs red potatoes 1 tbsp minced garlic 1 tbsp italian seasoning 1 tsp red pepper flakes 1 tsp salt  1/2 tsp pepper 1 tbsp avocado oil  1 can coconut cream  2 cups chopped kale  Instructions: ✨ 1. Heat a large pot to medium heat. Add 1 tbsp of avocado oil and the ground chicken and pork. Cook for around 10 minutes until the meat has browned and is fully cooked.   2. Once the meat is cooked, add the minced garlic, chopped onion, and seasonings. Mix well. Saute for about 5 minutes until the onions are soft. *if you don’t like it spicy, reduce the amount of red pepper flakes to 1/4 tsp.  3.  Next, add the chopped potatoes and chicken stock. Bring to a boil, then turn the heat down to low, cover & simmer until the potatoes are soft—about 10 minutes.   4. Once the potatoes are cooked, remove from the heat and add 1 can of coconut cream and about 2 cups of chopped kale. Stir until the kale has wilted. Serve immediately & enjoy!   #makedinnerwithme #easyweeknightdinner #healthydinneridea #dinnervlog #easydinneridea

I am blend together half a cup of balsamic vinegar, 2 tablespoons honey, 1 tbsp dijon mustard, 1 tsp salt, 1/2 tsp garlic powder, 1/4 black pepper, and 1 cup extra-virgin olive oil 🍠 peal and cube potato toss in olive oil on sprinkle salt roast at 425F for 30 minutes 🍗 seasoned chicken breast liberally with salt, pepper, garlic powder and onion powder, placed on air fryer tray and then air fry at 400F for 17 minutes flipping once after 13 minutes 🍋 for snack I use the French yogurt cake recipe to make lemon poppyseed muffins #mealprep #nurselife

The video is long, here's the list written out. Let me know if y'all want more recommendations. 1. Don't assume the roads will be drivable and the sidewalks walkable (if a truck is swerving, maybe your camry also isn't equipt) 2. Invest in ice cleats (amazon is cheaper than REI) 3. Get a pair of gloves, a beanie, and a headband (I like the North face etip gloves, costco merino wool, turtle fur headband, all under $20) 4. Get winter boots (Sorel + Pajar are great and Nordstrom rack + Marshals carries them) if you can, but fuzzy crocs also work 5. Keep your apartment at 78 (and ignore Oncur) 6. Get a fleece + waterproof dog jacket (I like ruffwear and only own one jacket per dog) 7. Stock up (don't hoard) on doggie bags 8. Pipes burst, be prepared to quickly seal off your apartment (duck tape + towels can work in a pinch) 9. Charge your battery packs (Living near a hospital doesn't mean you won't lose power) 10. Listen to the basic. Get blankets, get water (cooking/toilet), fill water bottles #freeze #prep #advice #list #greenscreen #winter #coldfront #polarvortex

‼️ Couples camping hack ‼️ We are ALWAYS looking for ways to improve our tent sleep system so I can’t believe it took us this long to make the change from one double to 2 singles for our sleeping bag setup! WHY 2 singles? - They pack down SO MUCH BETTER than one massive double.  We used to have a really hard time packing around our double bag since it pretty much took up the entirety of our backpacking pack - The mummy style is actually much warmer than the box style on the double - With 2 singles, we’re able to go on solo adventures or adventures with friends without each other - We can customize the warmth (and length) of our individual sides of the bag!  I sleep so much colder than Sentry so I opted for a 0 degree bag, while he got a 15 degree bag.  And Sentry is obviously quite a bit taller than me so for his half he got a “long” version, giving him enough room to stretch his legs - We cut the weight of our sleep system in HALF… I actually couldn’t believe how much less it weighs to have the 2 singles than our one double.  Game changer WHICH ones? Okay this is important!!! You cannot just zip 2 random singles together… it will not work.  You need to get the same brand & make sure they have a compatable zip feature!  We have the @seatosummit altitude and the @seatosummit ascent.  They are both down filled and super lightweight- perfect for backpacking.  They also compress down to an impressively small size and each have multiple vent zips you can use for warmer nights. & they zip together seamlessly 😎 We are LOVING the change so far, but curious as to what you think?! One double or 2 singles 👀 let us know in the comments 👇🏼 . . .  #campinggear #campingsetup #campinggear

$15 Budget Dollar Tree Date Night Appetizer, Dinner, & Dessert! Full Recipes and Price Breakdown: Appetizer: Pickle Fritters Dill pickles $1.25 Southern fry mix $1.25 Ranch for dipping $1.25 Appetizer Cost $3.75 Drain entire jar of pickles and chop finely.  Mix chopped pickles with dry fry mix until a tacky dough forms (for me this was about 1/4 to 1/3 of a cup of fry mix)  I pan fried these fritters in oil until cooked and then I drained on paper towels and I fried them a second time to get them ultra crispy.  Serve with ranch for dipping.   Main course: Creamy Gnocchi Skillet  Gnocchi $1.25 Sausage $1.25 Frozen Pepper stir fry $1.25 Cream cheese blend $1.25 Parmesan cheese $1.25 Mozzarella cheese $1.25 Main course cost $7.50 Bring a large pot of water up to a boil, cover and set aside.   In a skillet, fry and crumble the sausage until brown, do not drain.  The sausage fat will add extra flavor.  Add 2 handfuls (about half the bag) of pepper stir fry (mine was thawed) and sautee for a few minutes.  Stir in 6 oz of cream cheese blend cut into cubes and about 1/2 to 3/4 of a cup of the boiled water we had set aside earlier.  Continue to heat and stir until you have a smooth and creamy sauce and stir in 1/4 to 1/2 cup Parmesan cheese to taste.  Taste and season if desired.  Set aside. Return to your boiling water and cook your gnocchi for 3 to 5 minutes until it starts to float to the top.  Do not overcook this or it will be gummy.  As each gnocchi floats transfer them to your prepared cream sauce.  Gently stir the gnocchi and sauce together, top with mozzarella and broil until brown on top.  Desert: Cherry Cobbler  Muffin mix (mixed berry or blueberry) $1.25 Cherry pie filing $1.25 Vanilla ice cream $1.25 Desert cost $3.75 Mix muffin mix with 1/2 cup of water or milk.  Add cherry pie filling to the bottom of a baking dish and top with muffin batter.  Bake at 400 degrees for 20 to 25 minutes and serve warm with ice cream. #valentinesday #datenight #datenightideas #dollartreedinners #budgetdinners #budgetdatenight

@hungryjack Bacon Upside Down Pancake You will need: 2 cups of Hungry Jack Buttermilk pancake mix 6 ounces of bacon 3 tablespoons of butter 1/3 cup of brown sugar  Nonstick cooking spray Syrup for topping Chop the bacon into smaller pieces and and fry until crisp, drain and set aside. Spray an 8 or 9 inch round cake pan with nonstick cooking spray and pour in your melted butter.  Layer on the brown sugar and spread evenly.  Top with cooked bacon.  Mix Hungry Jack pancake mix with 1 & 1/2 cups of water per the box instructions and pour over your bacon topping.  Bake at 350 degrees for 30 to 35 minutes until golden brown on top.   As soon as you remove it from the oven, invert it onto a plate, cut into 6 slices and serve with syrup. 10-minute egg drop soup that’s better than takeout! 🥚 INGREDIENTS (4 servings): 4 cups chicken broth 3 eggs, whisked ¼ tsp salt ½ tsp chicken bouillon ¼ tsp garlic powder ¼ tsp ground ginger ⅛ tsp white pepper ¼ tsp turmeric (optional) 1 green onion (topping) ½ tsp sesame oil (topping) 2 tbs cornstarch 3 tbs water DIRECTIONS: 1. In a pot, add broth & seasonings. 2. Taste, adjust seasonings to liking. 3. Make slurry w/ cornstarch & water. 4. Pour slurry into broth to thicken. 5. Stir in a circle to create a tornado. 6. Pour in eggs & stir slowly in circle. 7. Top w/ sesame oil & green onions. #eggdrop #soup #chinesetakeout #eggdropsoup #asiancooking #souprecipe #quickrecipe

Replying to @Fitzjitsu my healthy addiction #eggdropsoup #chinesetakeout  32oz carton of chicken or bone broth (4 cups) 1 Tbsp soy sauce 1/2 tsp garlic powder 1/2 tsp turmeric  1/2 tsp chicken bouillon powder 1 tsp white pepper Cornstarch slurry (3 Tbsp cornstarch + 4 Tbsp water)  3 eggs mixed w/ 1 Tbsp water 1 tsp sesame oil Bring your chicken/bone broth to a boil and add in your soy sauce and seasonings. Pour in your cornstarch slurry as you stir and wait for the broth to thicken just a bit. Once thickened, turn the heat down and make sure your broth is not bubbling to avoid your soup from getting cloudy. Slowly pour in your egg mixture as you stir to create long egg ribbons. Cut the heat and add in sesame oil. Garnish with lots of green onion razzle dazzle and enjoy!

This is the most dangerous city in the United States.   It’s Bessemer, Alabama, found just west of Birmingham, and it has a violent crime rate of 33 per 1,000 residents, almost nine times more than the national average.  The town has a population of 26,000 and presents a blend of everyday life, but it also is home to an eerie abundance of abandoned structures, ranging from historic residences to shopping malls and even football fields. This is why I insist that parents need support: they’re healing themselves, they’re healing their children, they often need to heal some parts of their marriage, and for many parents, they’re also supporting the physical + medical needs of THEIR OWN aging parents in the background! And ha, not to mention if they’re employed 🙃🙃 This is why family therapy is so important. We MUST begin by supporting the parents so that they can lead the healing of their family.  In the family therapy that I have been extensively trained in and practice, Emotionally Focused Family Therapy, we divide therapy into two phases: 1) parental openness 2) child vulnerability. We do not bring the child and parent together until the parent is open to the child’s needs and vulnerability. This protects the child from getting hurt further and sets the parent up to successfully work with their child.  I decided to role play this particular dyad 1) bc I see it in around 1/3rd of mom-daughter dyads that I’ve worked with 2) I also saw a good bit of this in the comment section of that viral post about parents taking accountability. More than one comment outright said, “they should validate me.” Lol.  My aim is not to attack mothers or fathers. It is to show where things go wrong and how that creates pain that then becomes a legacy of pain when we pass it down to our children. Family therapy involves examining our own relationships and experiences as children, identifying the pain that we have there, and working to heal both our own pain and that of our children’s. And this is what the work looks like right from the first parent session.  #familytherapy #family #mom #dad #kids #dysfunctionalfamily #childhood #childhoodtrauma #cptsd #trauma #nocontact #nocontactwithparent #relationship #telationships #communication #attachment #attachmentstyle #attachmentissues #anxiousattachmentstyle #avoidantattachment #anxiousattachment #therapy #therapysessions #therapytiktok #therapist #mentalhealth #skit #roleplay #fyp #foryou #parenting #parenting101 #parentingtip #parents #parent #parentifiedchild

CNN's Elizabeth Wagmeister interviews Gypsy Rose Blanchard, who was released from prison after serving eight years over a plot to kill her abusive mother, Dee Dee Blanchard. She pleaded guilty to second-degree murder in 2016 and admitted that she convinced her then-boyfriend to stab her mother to death. Blanchard was a victim of Munchausen syndrome by proxy, a rare disorder in which a caregiver feigns or exaggerates illness in someone to elicit attention or sympathy. She had spent her childhood and early adulthood believing she suffered from a host of serious ailments, including leukemia, muscular dystrophy and asthma. After the abuse she experienced at the hands of her mother came to light, Blanchard was sentenced to 10 years in prison and released two years early on December 28th. According to the Missouri Department of Corrections, she is expected to remain under parole supervision until June 2025. #cnn

Garrett of Silent Planet is absolutely killing it at the moment. If you haven’t yet heard “Superbloom”, do yourself a favor. I believe that, now with fry screaming in the toolbox, he has been spared the torment that nearly ended his career in Europe in 2018 and everything is just plain easier. That doesn’t mean he does fry screaming all the time!    Fry screaming is NOT the only “right way to scream”! There is no ‘right way’, only wrong ways. And the wrong ways eventually lead to injury. “Fry screaming” is NOT “vocal fry” There are some similarities, however the experience of fry screaming is so vastly different, it is not helpful comparing it to vocal fry. Learning fry screaming opens a whole new world of resonance and effortless power and improves ALL the other kinds of screaming that involve greater throat constriction. Ask Garrett or ask Jesse Leach of @Killswitch Engage and they are sure to agree that fry screaming awareness proved to be a game changer.    Fry screaming has flow phonation mechanics like singing. Transitions in and out of melodic passages are seamless even within a single lyric. The added resonances provide variability and dynamics, without which screaming can be monotonous and generic.    Wanna dive deeper and learn how to do it too? How to fix skinny-fat🙃 “Skinny-fat” is confusing? Because the more weight you try and lose, the worse the problem seems to get? That’s usually because people are trying to solve the wrong problem💡 The problem most people *think* they need to solve is having too much body fat. They try and solve this by: - adding endless cardio - and restricting food more and more But that’s only going to make the problem worse Because “skinny-fat” doesn’t usually come from not having too much body fat, it comes from not having enough *muscle* underneath our fat to give us any shape or definition. To fix this, you would want to: - Focus on lifting heavy weights - Actually limit your cardio (probably not more than 1/3 of your total exercise) - And often times actually eat *more* food, not less It’s also important to note that every human body is different, so the exact solution for each person will be a little bit different - but this generally a good place to start 🤘🏼 #skinnyfat #abs #coreworkout #cardio #fittok

Replying to @Fitzjitsu my healthy addiction #eggdropsoup #chinesetakeout  32oz carton of chicken or bone broth (4 cups) 1 Tbsp soy sauce 1/2 tsp garlic powder 1/2 tsp turmeric  1/2 tsp chicken bouillon powder 1 tsp white pepper Cornstarch slurry (3 Tbsp cornstarch + 4 Tbsp water)  3 eggs mixed w/ 1 Tbsp water 1 tsp sesame oil Bring your chicken/bone broth to a boil and add in your soy sauce and seasonings. Pour in your cornstarch slurry as you stir and wait for the broth to thicken just a bit. Once thickened, turn the heat down and make sure your broth is not bubbling to avoid your soup from getting cloudy. Slowly pour in your egg mixture as you stir to create long egg ribbons. Cut the heat and add in sesame oil. Garnish with lots of green onion razzle dazzle and enjoy!

@L’Oréal Paris True Match Foundation's use of green pigment in its formulation is truly innovative. This green pigment acts as a powerful color tone enhancer, especially for folks with more olive complexions who often struggle with foundations appearing way too yellow. The green pigment neutralizes any excess warmth, ensuring a more accurate and natural shade match. Additionally, the inclusion of blue tones in some of their other shades addresses redness, making it a versatile solution for various undertones and shades. The customization and precision offered by this  approach cater to a wide range of skin tones, promoting inclusivity and accuracy in foundation matching. It’s pretty exciting to see the industry address these issues at the mass market level. I am curious to see what’s next for shade inclusivity. #thelipsticklesbians #beautytok #makeup #foundation

this def ruined any chance of being on the Pleasing PR list 🤭 for the line “c'mon, Harry, we don't wanna pay this much” 😞💜🍏🐝  #nailart #nailtutorial #watermarble #diy  Is it still overpriced? Hmmmmm maybe so - especially for cremes. I usually pay around $14 max for cremes but this set got me. I also read on the website that's its super sustainable, biodegradable, and made with recycled materials which could account for some of the price tag.   I couldn't find a dupe for the Pond Goo online, but the other colors probably have dupes. I'm still a sucker for these bottles and the matte finish top is especially cool, but I also have a bit of an excuse to buy them since I have a nail themed YT channel. I just don't know if it's worth it for someone with a regular amount of interest in nail polish. For collectors, nail polish fiends, and superfans? Potentially yes. All in all there''s so much detail in the packaging, which I'll probably keep, and the colors go so beautifully together and are more wearable I think than the first collection. I'd say if you're going to get polish from Harry Styles, only get the colors you truly want and will use, and I like the topcoat so maybe snag one of those if you're already paying for shipping. Also I'm ridiculously happy with how my water marbling turned out, I know it wasn't perfect but I felt like it fit the vibes of the collection and I want to do moooorreeeee. :)

simple chuck roast 🥩🔥 obviously you can add all sorts of veggies, spices, herbs ect but I love making a simple version at the beginning of the week to use for different meals 😋 All you need is - 2-4lb boneless chuck roast  - salt - pepper - garlic powder - 32oz container beef broth - any kind of oil  1. Cut roast into 4-6 equal size pieces  2. Coat liberally in oil, salt, pepper and garlic powder 3. Heat up Dutch oven before adding butter and oil on medium heat 4. Sear each side of beef until golden brown crust develops (will take time)  5. Remove fat and burnt bits from pot  6. Add in beef broth and Chuck roast and transfer to oven 7. Bake on 350° for 3-4 hours or until Chuck roast is tender and can shred with fork Notes :  - keep chuck roast covered if you are setting to the side after searing  - be careful opening lid after its been in the oven - store left overs in the remaining liquid to stay moist (i like to reheat the chuck roast in its own fat) So easy and delicious. If you guys try it tag me so I can see 😍

#ad Save this 10 minute balanced meal with @Birds Eye ! Frozen veggies are the key ingredient to making a nutritious, balanced meal in just 10 minutes. Unlike fresh vegetables, the prep is done for you because there’s no washing, peeling, or chopping needed. Plus, Birds Eye frozen vegetables last longer in the freezer than fresh vegetables, so you don’t have to worry about wilted veggies being wasted in the fridge. Here’s how to make this quick and easy 10 minute balanced meal! Birds Eye SteamFresh Broccoli: Cook according to package directions in the microwave. Microwave baked potato: Poke holes in a small russet potato and then microwave for 5-6 minutes, turning halfway. Quick tahini sauce: 1 tbsp tahini, 1 tsp honey, ¼ tsp garlic powder, lemon juice and salt to taste Stuff the baked potato with shredded rotisserie or leftover chicken, Birds Eye SteamFresh Broccoli, feta cheese and then drizzle with tahini sauce and enjoy! Check out Birds Eye in the Frozen section of your local grocery store!

One pan sweet potato gnocchi with cheddar chicken sausage + baby broccoli! Recipe: 1. Heat a skillet over medium high heat and add a little olive oil. Cook sliced Trader Joe's Unexpected Cheddar Chicken Sausage until brown on both sides. Remove the sausage from the skillet. 2. Eeduce the heat to medium, and add Trader Joe's frozen Sweet Potato Gnocchi with Butter and Sage. Lay baby broccoli on top, pour in 1/4 cup water, cover the pan with a lid, and steam for 10-12 minutes until the broccoli is fork-tender. 3. Remove baby broccoli from the pan and stir the gnocchi, scraping up any brown bits stuck to the pan. 4. Serve everything in a bowl with salt and pepper and dig in! Hope you love this one 🧡

Microwave baked potato: Poke holes in a small russet potato and then microwave for 5-6 minutes, turning halfway. Quick tahini sauce: 1 tbsp tahini, 1 tsp honey, ¼ tsp garlic powder, lemon juice and salt to taste Stuff the baked potato with shredded rotisserie or leftover chicken, Birds Eye SteamFresh Broccoli, feta cheese and then drizzle with tahini sauce and enjoy! Check out Birds Eye in the Frozen section of your local grocery store!

#Ad Don’t spend all this time flipping individual small pancakes. Try this skillet pancake made with caramelized bananas! I made this skillet pancake using a serving of @lovemysilk Original Almondmilk, which is an excellent source of calcium and Vitamin E. As we head into the New Year, we’re all thinking about how we can feel better with our routines which is why I’m adding more Almondmilk into my mornings. Let’s all incorporate more Silk Almondmilk into our breakfast routines! Join the 7-day Silk Feel Planty Good Challenge during the month of January for a chance to win a lifetime of free breakfast on Silk. Stay tuned to learn how you can enter, in the meantime stock up on #SilkAlmondmilk #FeelPlantyGood See all Feel Planty Good Challenge details at challenge.silk.com. No purchase necessary. Void where prohibited. The Feel Planty Good Challenge is sponsored by Danone US, LLC. Open to legal residents of 50 U.S. & DC, 18 & older. Begins 12:00 a.m. ET on December 22, 2023 and ends 11:59 p.m. ET on January 31, 2024. For Official Rules, visit Challenge.silk.com. INGREDIENTS 1 cup all-purpose flour ¼ cup oats 2 teaspoons baking powder ¼ teaspoon baking soda ¼ teaspoon salt 1 large egg 1 cup Silk Original Almondmilk 2 tablespoons butter 1 banana, sliced in half vertically 2 tablespoons maple syrup INSTRUCTIONS 1. In a medium bowl, whisk together the flour, oats, baking powder, baking soda and salt. In another larger bowl, whisk the egg until blended. Whisk in the Almondmilk, then fold in the dry mixture until well combined. Set aside. 2. When ready to cook, heat a large nonstick pan over medium heat. Melt the butter on the skillet. Add the two halved bananas, pour the maple syrup on top, and cook undisturbed for 2 minutes or until the edges of the banana start to brown. 3. Pour the entire pancake batter over the caramelized bananas and spread evenly to the edges of the pan. Reduce heat to medium-low, cover, and cook, shaking pan occasionally, until underside is golden brown and top is almost set, 7 to 8 minutes. 4. Use a rubber spatula to help slide the pancake onto a plate, then place the skillet over the plate and invert back into the skillet. Cook, uncovered, until the bottom is light golden and a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean, about 5 minutes more. Cut into 6 slices and enjoy immediately.

WHEW ❤️❤️ lets bring in some abundance for New years  with this black eyed peas recipe ❤️ 💛⭐️✨  INGREDIENTS 👇❤️ 20 oz Dried black-eyed peas 3 cups Chicken broth 1 whole Red pepper diced 1 Green pepper diced 3 celery stalks diced 6 Garlic cloves minced 1/2 Onion diced 1 Turkey tails 2 Turkey necks 1 Turkey legs 1 lb bacon chopped Spices 1 tsp onion powder 1 tsp garlic powder 1 tsp adobo 1/2 tsp maggi seasoning 1 tsp onion powder 1/2 tsp cajun seasoning 1/8 tsp red pepper flakes 1 tsp all purpose seasoning 1 tsp paprika salt and pepper to taste 1. In a large bowl, Soak the black eyed peas overnight in enough water to cover them. 2. In a large pot, cook the chopped bacon until crispy. Remove the bacon, set it aside, and leave the bacon fat in the pot. 3.Sautee celery, onions and peppers in the same pot that you cooked the bacon. Then, add in strained black eyed peas. 4. Add the chicken broth to the pot, ensuring that it covers the black-eyed peas. Add additional water to ensure beans are fully covered. Stir in spices. 5. Place the turkey tails, turkey legs, and turkey necks into the pot. Allow the mixture to simmer until the black-eyed peas are tender and the turkey is cooked through (about 1.5 to 2 hours). 6. Serve the black-eyed peas and turkey stew with the crispy chopped bacon pieces on top. #holidayrecipes #blackeyedpeas

Thank you to @downy for partnering with me to explain how Downy Rinse & Refresh works and the best way to use it! So, here are some tips about Rinse from a 4th generation dry cleaner. Downy Rinse & Refresh is Downy’s biggest innovation in 30 years, it's a product inspired by our love for vinegar when doing laundry. Yes, a giant company actually listened to online cleaning tips 💕 Their scientists have taken the vinegar hack very seriously and finally released their answer; a rinse additive that removes the source of odor-causing residues on all fabrics. And why should you use Rinse instead of vinegar? That's because vinegar isn’t very concentrated, you need to use about 5 cups of vinegar in the rinse cycle to receive benefits. You only need ¼ cups of Downy Rinse & Refresh to receive the same benefits!!! Here are some tips on how to use it: 1) Use your usual detergent in the wash cycle.  If you’re using a laundry pac, don’t forget to add the pac directly to the drum BEFORE putting clothes in! 2) Pour Downy Rinse & Refresh directly into the fabric softener drawer or agitator cup or add it directly into the rinse cycle (depending on your machine). 3) Dose based on your personal preference – add as much to the fabric softener drawer as you’d like. You can even experiment with dosing based on your load size or the level of odor-causing residue you need to remove. 4) Do not measure using cap—use a measuring cup and OR pour straight into machine Also, you should know that Rinse takes the place of fabric softener. DO NOT use both at the same time.  #AD #DownyPartner #TidePartner #laundryhack #laundry #cleaninghack

Before and after 3.5 months of working on this house interior! (Take a look at our last video to see the exterior progress). Things are taking shape! We have 2.5 months left, and lots more to do, but having the walls and ceilings fixes feel like a major turning point!  Most of the remaining tasks are finishing work as opposed to prep, and that is massive for us mentally. Some of you are disappointed that we aren't having full replastering of the walls, but our budget and timeline could not be more relieved. So many things end up being far beyond the scope, that having the walls be under budget is huge! It is hard to even look at the old videos... the look, feel and smell is like night and day. People keep commenting that it's like the house can take a deep breath, and that could not be more accurate! We can also start taking deeper breaths as well!  We are so excited about the inside and outside taking shape!  But RIP the doorbell (it makes me physically upset to think about). This happened weeks ago during the clear out and I couldn't post about it because I was so sad. And they are hard to find original due to the toxicity... Everyone loves Chips Ahoy! and whether you are making these for yourself or others, they WILL be a hit. #easyrecipe #christmascookie #easydessert #holidayrecipe #chipsahoy #holidaycookies #cozychristmas     Ingredients  3 Tbsp. butter  5-1/2 cups miniature marshmallows (1 ½ cups reserved)  6 cups puffed rice cereal  28 CHIPS AHOY! Cookies, chopped, divided  Holiday sprinkle (optional)   Line 13x9-inch pan with foil, spray with cooking spray.   In large saucepan melt butter over low heat. Add 4 cups marshmallows and stir until completely melted. Remove from heat.   In a large bowl add marshmallow mixture, rice cereal, remaining marshmallows and ¾ of the Chips Ahoy! Cookies. Mix until evenly coated.    Press onto bottom of prepared pan. Top with remaining chopped cookies; press lightly into cereal mixture to secure. Cool completely.

Fried calamari is one of the most elite appetizers, prove me otherwise 🦑🔥 It’s light, crispy, tender and SO delicious. Growing up by the sea, my father has had this dish LOTS of time and it still remains one of his favorites to eat and make. That tradition was passed on to my brother and I.  I especially love this dish around the holidays. At my house we traditionally make this on Christmas Eve or day, frying it just as the guests arrive and serving it hot with a squeeze of lemon and some flakey salt.  🔑 Here’s the important tips: - combine 2 parts flour and 1 parts semolina for the coating - fry in light olive oil for extra flavor  - don’t overcook it, they only need a quick fry until golden - season with salt immediately out of the fryer  - enjoy right away with a squeeze of lemon  Question for you: which do you prefer the rings or tentacles?!!! ⬇️⬇️ #calamari #friedcalamari #holidayappetizers #flavorsbyale

‼️Attention is our most valuable asset that corporations, influencers, and celebrities try to extract from us. Corporations and celebrities ask themselves, how can we hook people in for the longest period of time, how long can we get them to keep talking about the barbie movie for, or the awful outfits at the met gala, or or or. And once the trend dies, we move on very rapidly because we are constantly getting b0mbarded with various content and need to allocate our attention accordingly. We wont allow the algorithms to find a new trend or celebrity or product that will dominate people’s lives. Takeaways from cleaning out my high school closet at age 27: 🕰️ Cleaning out your closet responsibly takes TIME. This whole process took me almost a year (and I still have some things I plan to give away once they’re seasonal again). It’s obviously a lot of effort, but I also appreciate how this large effort makes me more conscious of what I’m bringing into my closet. 👕 What you don’t want can still be desirable to others. I was able to give away 30+ cotton event t-shirts through my local Freecycle group. The lady claimed and picked them up the same afternoon, and said she’d use them for waxing antiques. ♻️ Finally, wanted to call out some cool clothing recycling initiatives: free underwear recycling by @Subset  + the $20 @For Days take back bag (which becomes credit you can spend on sustainable brands). PURRRfect turkey every time. Brine ✔️Butter ✔️BBL✔️ #thanksgivingturkey  Brine: 4 cups apple cider ~12 cups water 2 large oranges 3 sprigs rosemary 2 Tbsp peppercorns 4 bay leaves 1 1/2 cup brown sugar 1 1/2 cup coarse salt Turkey: 13 lb turkey 1 1/2 sticks of unsalted butter softened 2 sprigs rosemary 3 sprigs thyme 2 garlic cloves grated 1 Tbsp Tony’s or Creole seasoning 2 tsp onion powder 2 tsp garlic powder 1 tsp salt 1 tsp pepper 2 onions 4 carrots 4 celery stalks 1 head of garlic Extra rosemary & thyme  The day before, bring your brine to a boil and let cool completely before adding your turkey in. Refrigerate overnight (max 24 hrs) and the next morning discard brine and rinse turkey well. Pat dry and let sit out at room temperature for at least an hour.  Preheat your oven to 350. Mix the ingredients for your butter and add your veggies to the bottom of a roast pan. Using your hands, separate the skin of the turkey from the meat. Take small dollops of the butter and shove under the skin and rub some all over the surface, reserving about 1/4 cup. Transfer the turkey to your roast pan over your bed of veggies and shove some into the carcass along with your herbs. Tuck the wings and tie the legs with kitchen twine for even cooking. Melt the remaining butter and inject into the meat.  Insert a meat thermometer into the thickest part of the thigh making sure not to touch any bone. Roast your turkey in the oven 15 minutes per pound or until the internal temperature reaches 165 degrees. Rest for at least 30 minutes. Carve and enjoy!

$1 vs. $25 Canned Sardines 🎣 Tinned Fish Talk 🐟 Beach Cliff Sardines in Soybean Oil 🐟 PYSCIS Sardine Royale 2018 in Olive Oil The point here isn’t to say expensive is always better. I wanted a direct comparison between how sardines are most commonly perceived in the US and an opposite extreme of quality control. For those skeptical how a tin could cost $25 look beyond the can itself. The oil alone is many times more expensive, catch methods, selection, and packing require more labor, and conditions for aging must be maintained. Just as wine can range from $3 to $30, sardines can too. Some affordable tins I like include Trader Joe’s sardines in olive oil for $1.69 or King Oscar brisling sardines in EVOO (AKA Tiny Tots) for $3. Note that taste is subjective and this is just one opinion. At the end of the day buy what YOU like. Browse sardines ranging from $3 to $30 at Rainbow Tomatoes Garden (where I got the PYSCIS tin). This small business not only has the largest selection of tinned fish, they also vet every single one of their 800+ products. #tinnedfish #cannedsardines #sardines

Shaved brussels sprout salad with pomegranate, apple, dried cranberries, candied pecans, shaved parmesan and a creamy lemon dijon vinaigrette, aka my FAVORITE holiday salad!! RECIPE:  Serves 6 Ingredients: 12 oz shaved brussels sprouts, stems removed (we also like to remove the cores but this is optional) 1.5 cups pomegranate arils 1.5 cups honeycrisp apple, diced 1 cup pecans, chopped and candied or just toasted (optional - let me know if you want the recipe!) 3/4 cup dried cranberries 3/4 cup shaved parmesan 3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil 1.5 tablespoons freshly lemon juice 1.5 tablespoons apple cider vinegar 2 tablespoons dijon mustard 1 tablespoon maple syrup or honey 1 teaspoon salt 1/2 teaspoon pepper Using the shredder attachment on your food processor, an mandoline, a knife, shred your brussels sprouts into 1/16” shreds. You can also buy a bag of pre-shredded sprouts. For a better texture, cut off any extra woody stems on the sprouts. For the BEST texture, use a paring knife to cut out the core of the sprout. Combine the brussels sprouts, pomegranate, apple, pecans, cranberries and parmesan in a bowl. Whisk together all of the dressing ingredients, pour over the salad, and toss. Let the salad sit for about 30 minutes before serving. As it sits, the acid in the dressing will soften up the sprouts. Serve with extra parmesan, pomegranate, and pecans.  #salad #choppedsalad #saladsoftiktok #holidaytiktok

Starting off strong with Baked Ziti! It’s just one of those recipes that never fails. It’s comforting, satisfying, warm…everything you want on a cold day. Let me know if you make it ❤️‍🔥 - 2 T @Graza  - Yellow onion, diced - 1 head of garlic, minced, to taste - 1 t Italian seasoning - 1 t red pepper, to taste - Salt and pepper, to taste - @Tony Chachere original, to taste - 1 lb hot Italian sausage, can sub mild - 1 lb lean ground beef - 28oz @Rao’s Homemade Marinara - 1 lb Ziti - 15 oz ricotta - 1 egg - 2 cups mozzarella, more to taste - 3/4 cup parmesan, plus more for topping - Fresh parsley 1. Preheat oven to 375F 2. Boil your noodles in heavily salted water, 2 minutes less than package instructions (al dente). Drain and set aside. 3. In a large pot, heat olive oil over medium heat. Add in your onion, pinch of salt, Italian seasoning, and red pepper. Cook for about 5 minutes. Add in your garlic and cook until fragrant, about 1 min. 4. Add in your sausage and beef (you might need to increase the heat here a bit). Season with salt, pepper, and Tony’s. Brown and cook until no longer pink. 5. Add in your Rao’s and stir to combine. Taste and adjust seasoning as needed. Reduce heat to low and simmer. 6. While your sauce is simmering, combine your ricotta, egg, mozzarella, parmesan, salt, and pepper in a large mixing bowl. Stir until everything is fully combined. Add in about a ladle or two of your meat sauce followed by your cooked ziti. Fold everything together.  7. In a 9x13” baking dish, add a thin layer of your sauce followed by half of your noodle mixture. Top with half of your remaining sauce, followed by half of your remaining cheese. Repeat once more: noodles, sauce, cheese. Sprinkle parmesan over the top and bake for 15 minutes and then finish under the broiler for 5 minutes. 8. Sprinkle with fresh parsley, more parmesan, and enjoy! #winterrecipes #winterrecipe #foodseries #comfortfood #pastatok #pastarecipe #pastarecipes #pastabake #pastabakerecipe #bakedpastarecipe #bakedpasta #bakedziti #bakedzitirecipe #foodtok #easyrecipe #easyrecipes #zitipasta

Replying to @sorimonta85 extra fudgy chocolate cake with a rich chocolate ganache frosting! whip this up anytime whenever the chocolate craving hits 🍫 2 cups flour  2 tsp cornstarch 1 1/2 cups sugar 1/2 cup brown sugar  1/2 cup cocoa powder  1 1/2 tsp baking powder 1 tsp baking soda 1/2 tsp salt 2 eggs  2 tsp vanilla  3/4 cup buttermilk 1/2 cup vegetable oil 1/2 cup warm coffee  Ganache: 1 cup heavy cream 1 cup sugar 8 oz semisweet chocolate, chopped 6 tbsp unsalted butter 1. Whisk flour, cornstarch, sugars, cocoa powder, baking powder, baking soda, and salt.  2. In another bowl, whisk buttermilk, oil, eggs, and vanilla until smooth. Whisk in the coffee.  3. Make a well in the dry ingredients and pour the wet batter into the dry. Mix until combined.  4. Evenly pour the batter into two 9 inch cake pans. Bake at 350°F for 35-40 mins.  5. To make the ganache: add heavy cream and sugar to a saucepan over medium heat. Allow the mixture to come to a simmer, then remove from the heat. Pour into a bowl with chocolate and butter. Whisk until smooth. Refrigerate for at least 30 mins. 6. Allow the cake to cool before frosting. Enjoy!  #chocolate #chocolatecake #chocolateganache #bakingcakes

Holy moly this is ✨the one✨ Brown 4 sticks of salted butter Separate into two portions  Set 12-14 tablespoons for the cake aside in your kicing bowl and the rest is for the icing. Let the brown butter cool and solidify enough to be whipped Dry ingredients   ✨2 ¼ cups flour ✨1 ½ teaspoon baking powder ✨¼ teaspoon baking soda sift your dry ingredients together or you can use a whisk and whisk them together. Wet ingredients  ✨1 cup granulated white sugar ✨ 1/4 cup light brown sugar and 1/4 cup, dark brown sugar ✨3 eggs, at room temperature ✨1 tablespoon vanilla ✨1 C. buttermilk, at room temp Whip the 12 tablespoons of the cooled browned butter until it lightens in color then add your sugar and mix and then add your eggs and mix until it is light and creamy. Add in a little flour/bakingsoda/baking powder mixture and buttermilk at a time and beat until it’s just combined.  Put your cake batter into two cake pans lined with parchment paper on the bottom and bake for 20 to 25 minutes at 350°F. Let the cakes cool completely.  Icing  16 ounces of softened cream cheese  The remaining amount of the solidified brown butter  4 cups confectioners sugar, and a splash of vanilla extract  Whip the brown butter first. Then add in the cream cheese and whip them together. Then add the confectioners sugar one cup at a time and mix it together. If it starts to get too thick, add 2 to 4 tablespoons of heavy cream and continue to mix. This cake was Bussin Bussin. better than s*x cake🤭 need a last minute thanksgiving dessert? here’s a quick and easy one to make! Ingredients: - 1 Box of German Chocolate cake mix - 10 oz of caramel ice cream topping  - 1 can sweetened condensed milk  - 1/2 cup toffee bits - 3/4 cup chocolate chips - 1 small cool-whip    Directions: - Bake cake according to package directions - While cake is still warm, mix caramel and can of sweetened condensed milk until warm and well blended in small pan on low on the stove  - Poke holes all over the cake. Confetti Cake (yield: 1 8-in round cake) Confetti Cake 3 eggs, room temp 2 1/4 c (450g) sugar 8 oz (227g) butter, melted and cooled 1/4 c (50g) vegetable oil 3.5 c (420g) cake flour, sifted 1.5 tsp (6g) baking powder 1 tsp (6g) fine salt 1.5 c (341g) milk, room temp 1 tsp clear vanilla extract 1/2 tsp almond extract 1/2 c (90g) rainbow sprinkles 1. Using a whisk or the whisk attachment on a mixer, mix the eggs and sugar until thick, lightened in color, and approximately tripled in volume. 2. Stream in the melted and cooled butter and oil while mixing on medium speed. 3. Add one third of the dry ingredients, mix until combined, and add half of the wet ingredients. 4. Mix in another third of the dry, the rest of the wet, and finally the last third of the dry. Stop mixing as soon as you can't see any dry flour. 5. Add the rainbow sprinkles and mix in by hand. 6. Divide evenly between 2 8-in round cake pans that have been prepped with a circle of parchment paper and non-stick spray. 7. Bake at 350F (180C) for 40-45 minutes or until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out with wet crumbs. 8. Let the cakes cool completely before cutting off the tops, dividing in half, and stacking with the frosting. Frosting 8 oz (227g) butter, softened 4 oz (113g) cream cheese, softened 4 c (454g) powdered sugar, sifted 1 tsp (6g) fine salt 2 Tbsp (28g) heavy cream 1 tsp clear vanilla extract 1. Mix together the butter and cream cheese until fluffy and lightened in color. 2. Add the powdered sugar in 3-4 additions. 3. Mix in the salt, heavy cream, and clear vanilla extract. Note: this frosting recipe makes enough for a semi-naked finish to the cake. For a completely frosted cake, multiply the recipe x1.5. #baking #cake #learnontiktok

You’ll thank us later for this🤭👀 Recipe ⬇️  Ingredients 2 Lb cold water lobster tails, (about 6 small or 4 large tails) 3 Tbsp mayonnaise 1 Tbsp fresh lemon juice, + 2 teaspoons fresh lemon zest 1 Tsp H-E-B All-purpose Creole Seasoning 1/2 cup(s) celery, very finely diced 1 Tbsp fresh chives, very finely chopped 1 Oz baby arugula 3 Tbsp salted butter, room temperature 6 H-E-B Bakery Brioche Hot Dog Buns Instructions: Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Cook lobster tails in boiling water for 5 minutes and remove to a cold water/ice bath. Allow to cool while preparing dressing for lobster. In a mixing bowl stir together Mayonnaise, lemon juice, lemon zest, creole seasoning, celery andchives. Season to taste with salt, pepper, or additional creole seasoning. Using kitchen scissors, remove lobster meat from shell and chop into 1 inch pieces. Add to mayonnaise mixture and stir to combine. Set aside. Heat a large skillet over medium heat. Trim a very thin slice from the top and bottom of hot dog bun and butter lightly. Toast to a gold brown in skillet. Remove and set aside. Line each toasted bun with a little arugula and divide lobster mixture evenly between buns. Serve and enjoy! #lobster #lobstertok #lobsterroll

End of year reflections… 1. Try to be creative at least once a day, doesnt matter if it’s a doodle on a paper napkin or actually doing your favorite medium of art. Just keep using tour creative muscle.  2. Tell people you are an artist. I know this one is hard, but the more you put it out there, the more you will feel it is true. It doesn’t matter if you are not even making work or selling anything, you are an artist.  3. Invest in your work, yes having an art practice means buying material. I had to purchase alot for this loom which i was frustrated with but if i want to keep my career moving i must spend money on the material.  4. Ask for help, i am at a place in my career where there are things i am not the most experienced in so asking for help is huge. I don’t like admitting i need help but im working on this one. Whether its for marketing or for building my frames, i am starting to voice my need for guidance.  5. Accept where i am at. I have been really hard on myself thinking i should be somewhere further along in my career, but im not. Im exactly where i am and accepting that is hard but important because it is a journey and every step is important.  6. Making goals for myself though is important. Im not going to be where i want to be by just dreaming it, i need to create tangible goals that i can meet. The first is framing all my work i have made in the past year so i can start selling and displaying.  7. Kindess is key. Some days i am tired, and letting my body get rest when it wants to is key. Looking at my work with kindess, looking at myself with kidness, looking into the future with kindess. We can use more kindess in the world, it starts first with you. welcome back to my series where I’m turning a single $55 grocery list into 5 easy, healthy gluten-free & dairy-free meals — each recipe serves 3-4 & this is recipe #3! 💕 as a reminder, grocery list is in the caption of the first video! ingredients: - 2 tbsp olive oil  - 12oz chicken sausage, sliced (I use garlic flavor)  - 1 shallot, finely chopped - 3 garlic cloves, minced  - 1 tsp salt + additional to taste - 1/2 tsp black pepper - 1 tsp dried basil  - 1 tsp dried oregano - 1/4 tsp red pepper flakes (optional)  - 3 tbsp tomato paste - 12oz gluten-free pasta (~1 + 1/2 cups), cooked - 1/2 cup veggie broth (can sub chicken broth)  - 1/2 cup water - 1/2 13.5oz can full-fat coconut milk (about 3/4 cup) - 1/2 6oz bag baby spinach heat the olive oil on a large skillet over medium heat, then add the sliced chicken sausage to crisp, about 5 minutes each side. remove the chicken sausage from the pan and set aside. boil a pot of water. in the same pan, add the shallot and sauté, stirring frequently, for 4-5 minutes. add the minced garlic and cook for another minute, then mix in the salt, black pepper, basil, and oregano. let the spices get aromatic, about 2-3 minutes while stirring, then add the tomato paste. stir to incorporate the tomato paste into the shallot and garlic mixture. continue stirring until it turns dark red and easily spreads, about 3 minutes. meanwhile, add the pasta to the pot of boiling water and cook 7-9 minutes, until al dente. pour the veggie broth and water into the pan with the tomato paste mixture and mix to combine. bring to a simmer, then pour in the coconut milk. mix well and bring back to a simmer, continuing to stir until the sauce is a uniform mixture. reduce heat to low. drain the pasta. mix in the baby spinach to the sauce and allow it to fully wilt. add the cooked pasta and coat all of it in sauce. add back the chicken sausage. for best results, serve immediately. enjoy!! I am going to answer the number one question I get asked. “I don’t know how she carried her, I would have collapsed to the floor”. I did. I did collapse. The first day it happened and after the video in her hospital room. But in this moment I felt like I had superhuman strength. By the end I felt she was suffering if I held on any longer. I know they were making her comfortable but my mom heart could not take it. We got to spend days with her. Which will never compare to a lifetime. But I watched my daughter pass the day she went into cardiac arrest. Don’t under estimate your strength as a mom if you were in my situation. She was ready this day. I knew that. She fought a long fight the least I could do was to carry her in her final moments. I carried her into this world, I unfortunately had to carry her out. Sloane I love you. I miss you. This pain is more than any mother should know. So here is the original. They played the song I picked. It was playing everywhere I went that day. It just felt right. Thank you to this incredible staff.

LIONS MANE "STEAK" 🥩🍄 (Tag yourself, I'm the pan slowly moving away post fire)  INGREDIENTS:  - lions mane mushroom  - Avocado oil  MARINATE:  - 1/2 cup beetroot juice - 1 tsp garlic powder - 1 tbsp soy sauce - 1 tsp onion powder - 1 tbsp smoked paprika - Salt and pepper - 2 tbsp olive oil ASIAN STYLE SAUCE:  - 2 tbsp soy sauce - 1 tsp gochujang - 1 tsp rice vinegar - 1 tbsp brown sugar - 1 tbsp chili garlic  - Splash of Sesame oil HOW TO:  1. To make the cooking process easiest, I like to prep my sauces. In one bowl, add all marinade ingredients and stir together.  2. In a separate bowl, prep your Asian style sauce by adding all ingredients and stir together.  3. Heat up a pan with a drizzle of oil & salt  4. Add in mushroom and move it around to get used to the heat  5. With the use of another pan, rest on top of the mushroom to add some weight (no need to press down - learn from me)  6. Take top pan off and flip mushroom over to the other side to sear.  7. Repeat the process until it becomes a flat steak shape.  8. Place mushroom in marinade and drown that thing! Use a spoon to get it in all the places. Once done, place in fridge for 15 minutes or longer.  9. Remove from fridge and sear both sides again on the same pan (about 3 min each side) while coating with Asian style sauce.  10. ENJOY!!!  #lionsmane #vegetariansteak #vegetariandinner #vegetarian #mushroomrecipes #lionsmanerecipes

You’ll thank us later for this🤭👀 Recipe ⬇️  Ingredients 2 Lb cold water lobster tails, (about 6 small or 4 large tails) 3 Tbsp mayonnaise 1 Tbsp fresh lemon juice, + 2 teaspoons fresh lemon zest 1 Tsp H-E-B All-purpose Creole Seasoning 1/2 cup(s) celery, very finely diced 1 Tbsp fresh chives, very finely chopped 1 Oz baby arugula 3 Tbsp salted butter, room temperature 6 H-E-B Bakery Brioche Hot Dog Buns Instructions: Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Cook lobster tails in boiling water for 5 minutes and remove to a cold water/ice bath. Allow to cool while preparing dressing for lobster. In a mixing bowl stir together Mayonnaise, lemon juice, lemon zest, creole seasoning, celery andchives. Season to taste with salt, pepper, or additional creole seasoning. Using kitchen scissors, remove lobster meat from shell and chop into 1 inch pieces. Add to mayonnaise mixture and stir to combine. Set aside. Heat a large skillet over medium heat. Trim a very thin slice from the top and bottom of hot dog bun and butter lightly. Toast to a gold brown in skillet. Remove and set aside. Line each toasted bun with a little arugula and divide lobster mixture evenly between buns. Serve and enjoy! #lobster #lobstertok #lobsterroll

But this provides an excellent time for me to backwash and rinse the filter itself to help clean it. Normally, if I rinse and backwash, I have to fill up the pool with hose water, which can be expensive, so the rain provides an excellent opportunity to get a little free water. The only drawback is sometimes the rain can bring and when it chemicals to the pool itself, so I have to watch the fishes behavior to be sure they are good.

Cookies, chopped, divided  Holiday sprinkle (optional)   Line 13x9-inch pan with foil, spray with cooking spray.   In large saucepan melt butter over low heat. Add 4 cups marshmallows and stir until completely melted. Remove from heat.   In a large bowl add marshmallow mixture, rice cereal, remaining marshmallows and ¾ of the Chips Ahoy! Cookies. Mix until evenly coated.    Press onto bottom of prepared pan. Top with remaining chopped cookies; press lightly into cereal mixture to secure. Cool completely.

welcome back to my series where I’m turning a single $55 grocery list into your week of easy, healthy meals — this is recipe #1! 💕 if you’re new here, I post one recipe per day (5 total recipes) and all of them are gluten & dairy free and serve 3-4 people! the grocery list is in the previous video 😊  full recipe is below & also on my website!  ingredients: - 1 lb ground turkey - zest of one lemon - 2 tsp salt - 1/2 tsp black pepper - 1 tsp dried oregano  - 1 tbsp dried basil  - 2 tbsp olive oil  - 1/4 large yellow onion, diced - 3 garlic cloves, minced - 1 cup dry rice, rinsed  - 1 tsp smoked paprika + salt & pepper to taste - 1 + 1/2 cups veggie broth (can sub chicken broth) - 1/2 13.5oz can full-fat coconut milk (3/4 cup) - juice of 1 lemon - 1-2 cups water (depending on need) - 1/2 6oz bag baby spinach  preheat your oven to 400 degrees and line a sheet pan with parchment paper. in a large bowl, combine the ground turkey, lemon zest, salt, black pepper, oregano, and basil until it’s a uniform mixture. use a cookie scoop or spoon to shape the mix into ~12 even meatballs and place on the sheet pan. bake for 15-20 mins, or until the internal temp is at 165 degrees.  while the meatballs bake, heat the oil over medium heat in a large skillet. add the diced onion and sauté until translucent. add the garlic and cook for another minute, then mix in the rice and season with salt & pepper + the smoked paprika.  let the rice toast, stirring occasionally, for about 5 minutes then pour in the broth, coconut milk, and lemon juice. add 1-2 cups of water, depending on how much you need to completely cover the rice in liquid. mix to combine, then cover the pan and cook for 15-20 mins, until the rice is fully cooked.  mix in the baby spinach and wilt it down, then add the cooked meatballs on top and top with a drizzle of olive oil and additional lemon zest if desired. makes 3-4 servings. enjoy!! On the night of September 6th, 2018 Botham Jean (26) was m*rdered in Dallas, Texas by off-duty Dallas Police Department patrol officer Amber Guyger, who entered Botham's apartment and f*tally sh0t him.  Botham and Amber lived in South Side Flats, a four-story apartment complex located at the corner of South Lamar Street and Powhattan Street—two blocks northwest of the headquarters of Dallas Police Department.  The floor plans for each level of the building are mostly identical. Amber's apartment on the third floor (number 1378), in which she had lived for approximately two months by the time of the m*rder, was located directly below Botham's apartment on the fourth floor (number 1478). On September 6th, 2018 Amber left work at 9:33 pm at the end of a 13.5-hour shift. She drove to the apartment complex, parking her vehicle in the parking garage of the fourth floor at 9:46 pm. At this time, she was speaking over the phone with her partner, who had called during her journey home. The conversation lasted until 9:55 pm. Still armed with a handg*n but no longer wearing a body camera, Amber walked to Botham's apartment, supposedly believing it was her own and failing to notice any signs that she was on the wrong floor, including a distinctive red doormat outside the apartment. Attempting to unlock the door, she noticed it was ajar. She entered the apartment and found Botham, who was sitting in his living room eating ice cream, unarmed. Amber fired her handg*n twice at Botham, striking him in the chest. She would later testify that she believed him to be an intruder, and that she feared he would k!ll her. Amber called 911 at 9:59 pm. Botham was taken to a nearby hospital, where he d!ed from his wound. The Texas Rangers investigated the shooting, which led to Amber's arrest three days later. On November 30th, 2018 Amber was indicted on m*rder charges by a Dallas County grand jury. M*nslaughter charges would have merely required proof of recklessness, while m*rder charges require proof that the defendant intended to k!ll. The prosecutors alleged criminal intent for two reasons: firstly, they said her arrival at the wrong apartment (on the wrong floor) was not caused by tiredness, but rather caused by the conversation she had immediately prior with her lover trying to arrange a meeting that night, and secondly that she did not follow standard police protocol of not entering a building with a potential burglar inside and instead calling for backup from the police station, which was only two blocks away. On October 1st, 2019 Amber was found guilty of m*rder. The jury deliberated for six hours to reach the verdict of m*rder. The nexy day, Amber was sentenced to 10 years in prison.  Amber is currently imprisoned in the Mountain View Unit. #ad NO BAKE OATMEAL CANDY COOKIES with @Quaker Oats  🎉🤍 It doesn’t get any easier or more delicious than these no bake cookies that come together in under 10 minutes. They’re a special family recipe that uses one of my fav pantry staples - Quaker Oats. Quaker has over 145 years of experience in milling trusted oat products. They’re great for the holidays but really make for a delicious snack any time of year! Hope you love them as much as we do! Ingredients: 3 cups Quaker Quick 1-Minute Oats ½ cup whole milk 1 cup granulated sugar 1 tsp vanilla extract ¼ cup margarine (it's very important to use actual margarine because it stays smooth and soft when it's room temp or cold. If you use butter the texture of the cookies is all wrong) ½ cup smooth peanut butter 5 Tbsp cocoa powder Unsweetened shredded coconut (for topping) Method: 1. In a medium pot combine margarine, milk, sugar, and vanilla extract. Over medium heat, bring the mixture to a rolling boil. Let cook for 1 minute until the sugar is dissolved and the ingredients are well combined. 2. Turn off the heat and carefully stir in the peanut butter, cocoa powder, and Quaker Quick 1-Minute Oats. Mix until everything is well combined. 3. Using a small cookie scoop or two spoons, quickly drop mounds of the cookie batter onto parchment paper. Shape and gently press down to form circles. Top with unsweetened shredded coconut and refrigerate for a minimum of 30 minutes. It later was revealed that Timothy took prescription anti-depressants, which contributed to his inebriation. The fraternity was supposed to be alcohol-free after a suspension in 2009. In this state of intoxication, he fell on the basement stairs of the house and was knocked unconscious. He was carried to a couch, where surveillance cameras captured a conspicuous bruise that bloomed on his left abdomen; however, this was shown to have originated from another one of the alcohol-fueled rush events for fraternities that Timothy had attended a week earlier. Jonah Neuman, Lars Kenyon, and Edward Gilmartin colluded in prohibiting witnesses from calling 9-1-1. Jonah threw someone against a wall, Edward labeled witnesses crazy and insane, whilst Lars downplayed the concerns of witnesses in group chats. Some time later, Timothy regained consciousness and rolled off the couch. Three brothers picked him up and placed him back on the couch. Security footage shows them poking Timothy in the face, to determine if he was okay, but he remained unconscious and unresponsive. At around 3:30 am on February 3rd, Timothy tried to get up, but once he reached a standing position, fell backward. He continued to stand up only to repeatedly fall back down. Once he was finally able to maintain balance, he staggered toward the lobby area of the house, but fell again headfirst into an iron railing and landed on a stone floor, likely incurring serious head trauma. He got up and tried to reach the front door but fell headfirst into it, knocking himself unconscious again. He later tried once more to ascend the basement stairs and was missing until several of the fraternity brothers discovered him several hours later behind the bar in the basement, cold and breathing rapidly. It was at this point that he was carried upstairs. After several minutes of debating on what the next step should be, the conclusion was made that Timothy’s injuries were indeed serious and that he would require medical attention. Before emergency assistance arrived, the brothers wiped bl00d from his face and attempted to dress him in an effort to warm him. At 10:48 am, emergency services arrived and Timothy was brought to Mount Nittany Medical Center, but was quickly transported to Penn State Milton S. Hershey Medical Center because of the severity of his injuries. Upon arrival, Timothy was rushed into surgery, where he was discovered to have a ruptured spleen and class IV hemorrhagic shock. His brain had swollen to the point that roughly half of his skull had to be removed to relieve the pressure. The surgeons attempting to save his life deemed the injuries to likely be nonrecoverable, and Timothy was pronounced d*ad in the early morning of February 4th, 2017. He was estimated to have had a bl00d alcohol content of nearly 0.40 on the night of the hazing incident. Timothy’s d*ath led to the largest criminal indictment against a fraternity and its members in American history. More than a dozen students were initially charged, some with involuntary m*nslaughter. Some of the most serious charges were dropped and others thrown out by judges. In March 2017, the Beta Theta Pi fraternity was permanently banned from Penn State.  In 2019, four members of the fraternity received sentences of one to nine months in jail and house arrest.  #truecrime #truecrimetiktok #timothypiazza

The Inner Work can help you understand, address, and heal any and all human issues you may find yourself struggling with. In the case of perfectionism, we have gone through traumatic experiences that imprinted our subconscious with an intimidation of wrongness and mistakes. Usually religion or harsh parenting where wrongness or mistakes are met with extreme rejection or punishment are a common source. Perfectionism is the mind trying to overcompensate for this paranoia by intimidating us to be perfect “or else.” So even after the original intimidation is removed our subconscious continues the pressure because it still thinks it’s keeping us safe. In order to heal from this we need to actually allow ourselves to make peace with our humanness and realize we can only do the best we can in each moment with what we know at the time.  Mistakes and consequences that are uncomfortable are a natural part of life and are not personal. To make a mistake just means you have to go through the consequences of that choice and learn, but the mind of perfectionism makes us feel like it is life or death. This is a crippling pressure and internal stress overtime. Whoever originally passed this belief system onto us had not learned any grace in life themselves and most likely live in their own internal torture of impossible standards.  True self-confidence doesn’t come from being perfect all the time, it actually is the ability to recover from any setbacks with ease, grace, and most importantly optimism for the lessons learned. The irony is when we have this more relaxed confidence we tend to show up our best. Get The Inner Work to learn more about the healing journey and how to reach your full potential of a life of true freedom and lasting happiness. Happy Halloween! 🎃 Here are 5 easy ~last minute~ Halloween costumes for couples with stuff you probably already have in your closet ♻️  An investigation in 2019 showed that 83% of Halloween costume materials were oil-based plastics (think plastic masks, synthetic fibers, fish nets, etc). This equates to approximately 2000 tons of plastic waste generated by halloween costumes every year!! We all love a good costume, but not when it’s only going to be worn once and then thrown away (or never worn again).   Instead, here are some sustainable alternatives for Halloween costumes (whether for this year, or next!)  🎃Try looking at what you can create with clothes + accessories already in your closet—you’ll be surprised by what you can piece together by looking for inspiration online  👻Check out your local secondhand / thrift store for Halloween costumes / accessories! Plus, you’ll save money than buying retail price.  🩸If buying new, plan to wear/use it again for future halloween festivities! *No one is really going to remember what you were last year 😉  🦇 Don’t throw away your costume if it’s still in good shape. If you’re looking to clean out, see if any secondhand stores will take them! (Sometimes they will buy in costumes and keep them in storage until the following year to have a good selection of inventory).  ⚠️REMEMBER! Your Halloween costume could already be living in your closet 🧟‍♀️  #sustainablehalloween #costumeideas #couplecostumeideas #easyhalloweencostume #lastminutehalloweencostumes #couplecostumes2022 #sustainablecostumeideas

What to do in The Berkshires in Lenox, Massachusetts 👇🏻 After spending time in The Berkshires for a perfect spooky, fall weekend last year, I was able to take away some tips for things to do when you’re visiting the Lenox and Stockbridge area.  Here are some of my favorite spots:  📍The Mount, Edith Wharton’s Estate - A historic house museum and vibrant cultural center with a variety of tours, programs, and events to enjoy.  📍 Berkshire Scenic Railway Museum - An all-volunteer, non-profit organization dedicated to preserving railroad history and artifacts. The museum offers fun and educational train rides using restored vintage railroad equipment. 📍 Ventfort Hall Mansion and Gilded Age Museum - Ventfort Hall was one of the approximately seventy-five so-called “Cottages” built in Lenox in the late 19th century when the village became a popular Gilded Age resort. 📍 Naumkeag - A 48-acre architecturally stunning public garden and historic home.  📍 October Mountain State Forest - A 16,00 acre park with hiking trails for any level of experience, wildlife and a plethora of outdoor activities.  📍 Yankee Candle Store - A multi-level, rustic and beautiful candle store to explore and buy scents that remind you of the mountains and holidays of the season.  ✔️ Save this for your adventures in The Berkshires! #theberkshires #lenoxma #westernmass #westernma #westernmassachusetts

Before we started dating, hed often call me by her name, and never understood why i got so upset over it. He would say how much he “hated her”. I knew that meant he still liked her. I often times thought he was with me to get over her.  He would always bring her up, and wouldnt understand why it would always break my heart. I cried so much over it and he knew it. After a big fight over it, he told me he unfollowed and blocked her. When she got a boyfriend he magically became best friends with him. I never told him how that made me feel because i knew hed say i was over thinking it. I grew to hate her because she was everything i wasnt. She was effortlessly pretty and i wasnt. She had him the way i wish i did. After he broke up with me, i notced her refollowed her. That made me feel like evrything i ever thought was true. When she found out about the breakup she checked in on me. She comforted me and told me i will feel better one day. I feel so bad for ever hating her. Ive known her since 6th grade and she has always been the sweetest person to me.

let’s make french onion soup beans🫘  ✨gluten free, vegetarian, and can be made vegan too ✨INGREDIENTS✨ 3 tablespoons unsalted butter🧈 2 tablespoons olive oil  🧅2 white onions  1 teaspoon salt 1 teaspoon cracked black pepper 2 tablespoons (gluten free) flour 1 cup beef (or vegetable) stock 2 cans butter beans🫘 2 tablespoons white miso paste (optional) fresh thyme 1/2 cup shredded gruyère (optional)🧀 parsley ✨DIRECTIONS✨ 1. slice white onions and caramelize in your pot with 2 tablespoons of butter and olive oil. add salt and pepper.  2. once your onions are caramelized add 1 tablespoon of butter and the flour. stir.  3. add beef stock, beans, miso paste, and thyme. mix together and let simmer for at least 10 minutes.  4. mix in gruyère.  5. you’re now ready to serve and eat! garnish with parsley😋 #glutenfree #cheapmeals #frenchonion #beans
